![[Pasted image 20230220160716.png]]

Now we want to do that but in a computer, we want the minimum complexity possible, so we want to avoid repeating calculations.


# Algorithm
## Forward propagation 
You calculate the activity at every neurone 

## Backward propagation
Then you derivate according to it
$h$ : the activity at a neurone
$$
\frac{ \partial E }{ \partial w } = \sum\limits_{  \alpha\in p } \frac{ \partial e^\alpha }{ \partial y }.\frac{ \partial y }{ \partial w }   
$$
the $\frac{ \partial e^\alpha }{ \partial y }$ is easy to calculate
$\frac{ \partial y }{ \partial w }=\frac{ \partial y }{ \partial h }\frac{ \partial h }{ \partial w }$
$\delta = \frac{ \partial y }{ \partial h }$
Then you calculate the local error : $\delta^L$ but it depends on $\delta^{L+1}$ etc...
then once you have calculated all the needed $\delta$s you update the needed weight.

![[Pasted image 20230220163709.png]]
The complexity gain comes from the fact that you can reuse the $\delta$ calculations for different weights.

/Science/Bayes-Decision-theory.title: Bayes Decision theory
/Science/Bayes-Decision-theory.content:
Likelihood function :: 

![[Probability distribution#Density Function]]
We are interested in $P(w_{j}|x)$
$\omega_{j}$ : the classe of element $j$
$x$ : the feature vector
**Prior** : $P(\omega_{j})$
**Likelihood** : $p(x|\omega_{j})$
Density function of measurements : $p(x)$
**Posterior** : $P(\omega_{j}|x)$ *Is what we are interested in*

Knowing $p(x|\omega_{j})$,$P(x)$,$p(\omega_{j})$ we can find $P(\omega_{j}|x)$
Bayes Theorem : 
$$
\begin{align}
P(\omega_{j}|x) = \frac{P(x|\omega_{j})\times P(\omega_{j})}{P(x)}
\end{align}
$$
Then to take a decision on what class the unkown belongs to we take the $argmax$ and use it's special properties to make it into a more conveniante form

$$
\begin{align} \\
\underset{j}{argmax}(P(\omega_{j}|x) ) = \underset{ j }{ argmax }(\frac{P(x|\omega_{j})\times P(\omega_{j})}{P(x)})\\
= \underset{j}{ argmax }(\log(P(x|\omega_{j})\times P(\omega_{j}))) \\
= \underset{ j }{ argmax }(\log(P(x|\omega_{j}))+ \log(P(\omega_{j})))
\end{align}
$$

The classifier found is **optimal**.

#### Problem :
We don't know $p(x|\omega_{j})$
We solve this using [[Maximum Likelihood]]

/Science/Determinant.title: Determinant
/Science/Determinant.content:
**Factor** by witch a linear transformation scales any area on the span

![[Determinant 2022-11-08 16.59.02.excalidraw]]

- If $\det M = 0$ then the linear transformation puts all of space onto a single point, every shape on the space has area 0.

- If $\det(A)<0$ the the transformation flippes the plane.
- It of course extends to the volume in 3D, etc

$$
\det(M_{1}M_{2}) = \det(M_{1})\det(M_{2})
$$
## Computation
Determinant of $2\times 2$ matrix 
$$
\det \begin{pmatrix}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{pmatrix} = ad-bc
$$

Determinant of $3\times 3$ matrix

Runs code in a totally isolated envrironment, is OS Indepedant



### Something that helped

Let's walk through each step you're asking about in your requirements:

1.  Pull from GitHub - You won't pull a docker image from here, however you may pull a Dockerfile from here, which would be used to build an image. The command to do this would be just like cloning any other repository: `git clone <repository url>`
2.  Build the image on ec2 - First you will need to have docker installed on the ec2 instance. Assuming you're running Ubuntu on your ec2 instance, follow the good instructions on Docker's page ([https://docs.docker.com/install/linux/docker-ce/ubuntu/](https://docs.docker.com/install/linux/docker-ce/ubuntu/)) [miror](https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://docs.docker.com/install/linux/docker-ce/ubuntu/). Once docker is installed, navigate to the directory that has your Dockerfile in it (cloned from git) and type `docker build . --tag mytag`
3.  Push the image to ecr - To do this, you need to have the amazon CLI installed on your box, and you need an ACCESS_KEY_ID and SECRET_ACCESS_KEY from AWS IAM. Once you have these, configure your connection by storing them as environment variables, or by typing `aws configure` and entering them. Once your credentials are configured, log into ECR by typing `aws ecr get-login --no-include-email`, and then copy/pasting the command it gives you. (you can also put ` around it to skip the copying step). This will allow you to push to ecr using docker push.

/Science/Dot-product.title: Dot product
/Science/Dot-product.content:
The [dot product](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product "Dot product") or **Scalar Product** (a special case of "inner product"), which takes a pair of coordinate vectors as input and produces a **scalar**.
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
1 \\
2 \\
3
\end{pmatrix}.
\begin{pmatrix}
4 \\
5 \\
6
\end{pmatrix}
=1*4+2*5*3*6
$$
![[Dot product 2022-11-12 16.37.38.excalidraw]]
### Properties
1. $\vec{v}.\vec{w}= \|projection\|.\|projected\|$
2. Order doesn't matter
3. $\mathbf{A}^{\top}B \Longleftrightarrow A .B$  I have seen it only for vectors


### Geometricaly:
- shows if a vector is in the same direction or using the projection
- If dot product with a univector it is equivalent to taking the length of the projection !
- (3) means that a dot product is a kind of linear transformation from $R^{2} \to R$ ! [[Duality]] A vector is in the end just a kind of transformation $\mathbf{\vec{v}}^{\top}$.

```This function appears to be responsible for evaluating the performance of a machine learning model on some data. It appears to be designed to evaluate the model over a number of batches of data, and to log various metrics of performance. The function takes in a number of arguments including:

-   `prefix`: a string that is used to prefix output log messages
-   `steps`: an integer representing the number of steps or iterations that have been performed so far
-   `model`: an instance of a `Dreamer` class, which appears to be the machine learning model being evaluated
-   `data_iterator`: an iterator that produces batches of data to be used for evaluating the model
-   `device`: the device (e.g. CPU or GPU) on which to run the model
-   `eval_batches`: the number of batches of data to evaluate the model on
-   `eval_samples`: the number of samples to use when evaluating the model
-   `keep_state`: a boolean indicating whether or not to keep the state of the model between batches
-   `save_size`: the size of the sample to save for future reference
-   `conf`: an object containing configuration options for the evaluation process

The function performs evaluation of the model in two steps: first, it performs "open loop" evaluation, in which the model makes predictions based on an initial set of observations, but does not receive additional feedback. Second, it performs "closed loop" evaluation, in which the model receives additional feedback in the form of rewards. For each step, the function logs various performance metrics, including log probabilities and losses. Additionally, the function logs the time it takes to perform the evaluation, and can save a sample of the data and model outputs for future reference.

PyDreamer author parcours :

```Hmm, gradually, I guess :) I started learning RL couple of years ago. Watched David Silver intro lectures, and later Sergey Levine lectures (really great) for more advanced topics. Along the way I tried to implement algorithms from scratch, to make sure I understand them - starting from DQN and A2C.

As for model based and getting to something like Dreamer, my advice is to start from supervised world model training. I.e. you can collect a bunch of data from the environment with any policy, store it as offline dataset, and then just train RSSM part of Dreamer as an image sequence prediction model. It is much faster and more stable to train, when you don't have to collect data online. And is pretty cool to watch these "video predictions", even if you're not running an agent. This split is actually still visible in my code - the train script just works on any dataset, and the agent/generator is completely decoupled.

Oh, and final thing, contrary to what some people say, you don't need crazy compute power. If you have just one good GPU it's enough to experiment with this. Even Atari envs train in a couple of days (mixed precision really helps!)
```

/Science/Eigenvalue-Decomposition.title: Eigenvalue Decomposition
/Science/Eigenvalue-Decomposition.content:
$A$ a matrix 
$W$ a matrix of eigenvectors of $A$ in its columns
$D$ a diagonal matrix with the corresponding eigenvalues on the the diagonal
Such that
$AW = WD$
$\Longleftrightarrow W^-1AW=D$ so you can also call it diagonalisation

## Geometric intepretation
$W$ contains the vectors that when transformed by $A$ are in the same [[Span]] but scaled.
$WD$ is a scalled version, by $d_{i}$ of the $W$ vectors.

# Overview of IoT Data Science Processes

## Mobile sensing with smartphones 
The different scales of data sensing are individual, group, community
There are two kinds of sensing :
- Participatory :: That asks people to be active in the data collection
- Opportunistic :: That collects any information possible, without requiring user action

Globaly we want to ![[IOT Data Science 2023-03-08 09.48.56.excalidraw]]
### Sense
Most difficulte part. 
- Android IOS api's
- Balance battery consumption
- Varying environments
- Get labels (for failure for example)
### Learn
- Statistics, Data mining
- Learning algorithms
Carefull we have to be able to scale the model to everyday use, with all the variablilty in people and everionments.
You can use crowdsoucing like the busines questions on google maps to improve labels.
We lack data.
## Inform share persuade
Data Visualisation, personnlized sevices
**Persuasive technology** :: systems that provide tailored feedback with the goal to change user's behaviour
**Motivation** : healthcare, envrionment awarness etc
**Method** : self reflection, goals and competions

There are privacy issues, in particular with people sensing the data of other people near by that maybe did not agree to that data collection.
## The different steps of the data pipeline in IOT activity recognition
### Data acquisition
You can vary the acquisition rate of the sensors
### Data segmentation
Sliding window,that can be triggered with energy theory.
It get's triggered when the energy is high ie when something is happening.
### Features extraction
You can use prior knowledge about the senses information to extract usefull features. 
For example : Model of the body
You can also extract average,Variance etc. to simplify the data.

### Model Building
...
### Evaluation
...


## IOT applied to industrial machines

There are a lot of different sensors for different applications
ex : vibration sensing, temp, oil composition

You have problems like the tradeoff between **Wired** and **Wireless** for the sensors, the notion of cost efficiency of the solution is important.

You have to get the data for the machines, that sometimes involves breaking a machine on purpose and recording the sensors

You can then do **sensor fusion** to use multiple sensors to detect a same event.


# Persuasive computing and context aware computing

## Context
The context :: is an abstract reprensentation of all the things surrounding the IOT device.
"any information that can be used to caracterize the situation of an entity"

We try to capture the context of a person, and can according to that adapth the experience.

Schmidt,Beigelm Gellersen's model
- every context has a unique name
- For each context a set of features are relevant
- And for each feature a range is determined

**Digital phenotyping** :: means personal digital footprints of biological, behavioral, and environmental data, captured either consciously or unconsciously by smart devices and wearables.

Definition of inner product
Definition 1 (Inner product) 
??
Let V be a vector space over IR. An inner product ( , ) is a function V × V → IR with the following properties 
1. ∀ u ∈ V , (u, u) ≥ 0, and (u, u) = 0 ⇔ u = 0; 
2. ∀ u, v ∈ V , holds (u, v) = (v, u); 
3. ∀ u, v, w ∈ V , and ∀ a, b ∈ IR holds (au + bv, w) = a(u, w) + b(v, w). Notation: V together with ( , ) is called an inner product space. <!--SR:!2023-01-06,1,230-->

/Science/Inverse-Matrix.content:
$$
A^{-1}A=I
$$
So geometricly you are just playing the transformation in reverse.
## Properties

- If $\det(A)=0$ then their is **no inverse**, all of space is squished into a lower dim(because *Volume* = 0) , so you can't unsquish. Think, how would that work ? see [[Determinant]]
- This is also the case if the $rank(M)< dim(M)$ because means it has been squished on lower dimensions as well. I think
- If $\det(A)\neq 0$ then there **is an inverse**.

/Science/L2-regularization.title: L2 regularization
/Science/L2-regularization.content:
Also called "Weight Decay"
## Definition
$$
\text{Error}=  \text{model}+\frac{\lambda}{2m}\times \|w\|^2
$$
with :
- $\|w\|^2_{2} = \sum w_{j}^{2}$  but varies for every kind of model we are optimising
- $m \text{ the number of inputs}$

## Intuition
The larger $\lambda$ is the more large weights are penalised, and so they reduce the extremisme / complexity of the model

Or for deep learning it is the [[Frobenius norm]]

/Science/Linear-Discriminant-Analysis.title: Linear Discriminant Analysis
/Science/Linear-Discriminant-Analysis.content:
Also called Fisher discriminant
Like [[Principle Component Analysis]] (reduces the number of dimensions) but focuses on maximizing separability among the known categories, and is a **supervised method**, cannot be applied on unlabeled  data
![[Linear discriminant analysis 2022-11-09 16.31.57.excalidraw]]
Finds the best axis onto which to project the data to maximize separability.
### How ?
1. Maximize the distance 
2. Minimize the variation which LDA calls "scatter" and is represented by $s^{2}$
3. ![[Linear discriminant analysis 2022-11-09 16.45.28.excalidraw]]
$$
\frac{(\mu-\mu)^{2}}{s^{2}+s^{2}}
$$
## Properties
- Not robust to outliers (Because also depends on covariance matrix)
Remedy to [[Estimation Bias]]
We can robustify it !
- You need to have the data Gaussian distributed ?
- And have similar covariance matrices for both ?

## Shrinkage

If the covariance matrix is the same for all data, then you get the same as with [[Bayes Decision theory]], but the lader assums we know everything about the data

/Science/Machine-Learning-1.title: Machine Learning 1
/Science/Machine-Learning-1.content:
We can find the optimal solution with [[Bayes Decision theory]] but we do not know the Likelihood $p(x|\omega_{j})$ most of the time, so we need to learn an approximate
first kind of learning is parameter estimation.
parameter estimation :: you take a type of probabitly distribution and try to guess it's parameters.

## Parameter Estimation
[[Expectation]]
[[Maximum Likelihood]]
[[Bayesian inference]]


## Classification without learning distributions
This enables us to not have to make an assumption about the form of the distribution.
[[Linear classification]]
[[Nearest centroid classification]]
[[Linear Discriminant Analysis]] or (Fischer discriminant because created by fisher)
[[Logistic regression]] #incomplet #TODO finish the video

Now we know all these great classification algorithmes, but they under perform on some high dimensional data because of the [[Curse of dimensionnality]]
You can use [[Principle Component Analysis]] to project into a lower dimension.
To optimise parameters you can use the [[Lagrange Multipliers]]
[[Singular value decomposition]] is another way of doing dimensionnality reduction, similar to [[Principle Component Analysis]]. 

## Generalisation error
With f the learned function and R : Risk minimisation
$R[f] = \int \frac{1}{2}|f(x)-y|^{2} \, dP(x,y)$
The problem we have it that P(x,y) is 
we can approximate the error of the model on this hypothetical data distibution $P(x,y)$ that we do not know, with the information we do know.
So we have to use the $N$ datapoints we do know to calculate the $f$ error
$R_{emp}[f] = \frac{1}{N}\sum\limits_{ i=1 }^{ n } \frac{1}{2}|f(x_{i})-y_{i}|^{2}$.
Now that we have this empirical error, how is the error going to **scale** with more N ?
- In other words, how is the **model** going to **generalise**.
- Do $R emp[f]$ and $R[f]$ converge ?
#### To predict $R[f]$ :
Use [[Cross Validation]], or use Error Bounds using model complexity with for example the [[VC dimensions]].

![[Pasted image 20221119150927.png]]

## Classifier generalisation (Learning theory)
We use hyperplane classifiers ie [[Perceptron]] bound there Risk Minimisation
$d<min\{ [R^{2}\|w\|^{2}]+1,n+1\}$
with $R:\text{ the radius of the smallest ball containing all the data}$
so when we use the 
### [[Empirical Risk Minimisation]]
$N$ : the number of points
$d$ : VC dimension
$$
R[f]\leq R_{emp}[f]+\sqrt{ \frac{d\left( \log \frac{2N}{d}+1 \right)-\log\left( \frac{\eta}{4} \right)}{N} }

## Definition
$$
\text{A set of distributions }\{ \mathcal{R}_{a}|\mathcal{A} \}
$$
- $\mathcal{A} \text{ is the set of actions}$
- $\mathcal{R}_{a} \text{ is a distribution on rewards, given an action}$
- At each step t the agent selects an action
- At each step t the agent selects an action
- The environment generates a reward $R_{t}\sim \mathcal{R}_{A_{t}}$
- Maximise Cumulative reward $\sum\limits_{ i=1 }^{ t }R_{i}$
- Using a policy $\pi$
## Further details
One armed bandit is a slot machine, it returns a positive reward with a certain probability, but you don't know that probability. The only way to find out is to test it out.
If you align multiple Armed bandits
There is an **underlying probability distribution**, **but you don't know it**, and you have to discover it.

## we can rewrite the sigmoid to make it stable

$$

\sigma(x) = \frac{e^{x}}{1+e^{x}} = \frac{1}{2}\Big(\frac{2e^{x}}{1+e^{x}}\Big) = \frac{1}{2}\Big(\frac{e^{x} - 1 + 1 + e^{x}}{1+e^{x}}\Big) = $$
  

$$\frac{1}{2}\Big( \frac{e^{x} - 1}{e^{x}+1} + 1\Big) = \frac{1}{2}\Big( \tanh\Big(\frac{x}{2}\Big) + 1\Big)

$$


```jupyter
sigmoid = lambda x: 0.5 * ( np.tanh(0.5 * x) + 1 )

sigmoid(x)
clipped_sigmoid(np.linspace(-12, 12, 100))
```

Other way to make it stable : clipping


```jupyter
np.clip(x, min_val, max_val)


def clipped_sigmoid_plot(x, min_val=-3, max_val=3):

    #print(np.clip(x, min_val, max_val))
    plt.plot(x, sigmoid(np.clip(x, min_val, max_val)), 'b', label='clipped')
    plt.xticks(np.arange(x.min(), x.max(), 3), fontsize=12)
    plt.legend(fontsize=20)
    plt.grid(axis='x')
    
clipped_sigmoid_plot(np.linspace(-12, 12, 100))
```

/Science/Odball-Paradigm.title: Odball Paradigm
/Science/Odball-Paradigm.content:
It is an experimental setting.
In the classical oddball paradigm (experiment) there are two kinds of stimuli (e.g., low and high tones; or green circles and red squares)
- Stimuli are presented at regular intervals in a random sequence. 
- One kind of stimuli is more frequent than the the other one, e.g., with a ratio of 80:20.
- The frequent stimuli are called standards and the infrequent stimuli deviants. 
- The test person has the task to ‘detect’ the deviant stimuli and, e.g., to count their occurences silently.
The deviant occurences are called **target**

# Objective
Reduce [[Model Variance]] ie [[overfitting]]



The regularization term helps to keep the optimisation procedure arround certain values
Sometimes we will se generalisation problems, to fight against those we can use [[Regularization]] to shape the learning surfaces in a certains way.

It helps keep the model less complex, so the model might fit the data less, but it will generalize well.

## Usage
We use the regularisation by **optimising** the regularisation term alongside the error.

$$
Risk = E_{T}(\mathbf{w}) + \lambda E_{R}(\mathbf{w})
$$
We optimise the $Risk$ function
with $E_{T}$ : training error
$E_{R}$ : prior knowledge of the solution ( artificial error we use to regularise/ constraint)
$\lambda$ regularisation parameter

We just put that into [[Gradient Descent]] procedure.
## Choice of $\lambda$
Choose your hyperparameter on the validation set (inversed in MI1)
You have to embed a cross validation for hyperparemter search, into another cross validation if you use cross validation.

/Science/Reinforcement-Learning.content:
A[Link to the lecture](https://www.deepmind.com/learning-resources/reinforcement-learning-lecture-series-2021)

"Science and framwork of learning to make decisions from interaction"

Reward hypothesis
Any Goal can be formalised as the outcome of maximising the **cumulative reward**



## Formalisation
![[Pasted image 20221117204232.png]]
![[Pasted image 20221117204248.png]]
![[Pasted image 20221117204300.png]]
Definition of Value v : is the expected value of the state
$$
v(s)= \mathbb{E}[R_{t+1}+R_{t+2}+\dots|S_{t}=s]
$$

Q is the expected value of states and actions
$$
q(s,a)= \mathbb{E}[R_{t+1}+R_{t+2}+\dots|S_{t}=s,A_{t}=a]
- A **policy** is a mapping of states to actions 
$$

1.  **Agent** — the learner and the decision maker.
2.  **Environment** — where the agent learns and decides what actions to perform.
3.  **Action** — a set of actions which the agent can perform.
4.  **State** — the state of the agent in the environment.
5.  **Reward** — for each action selected by the agent the environment provides a reward. Usually a scalar value.
6.  **Policy** — the decision-making function (control strategy) of the agent, which represents a mapping from situations to actions.
7.  **Value function** — mapping from states to real numbers, where the value of a state represents the long-term reward achieved starting from that state, and executing a particular policy.
8.  **Function approximator** — refers to the problem of inducing a function from training examples. Standard approximators include decision trees, neural networks, and nearest-neighbor methods
9.  **Markov decision process (MDP)** — A probabilistic model of a sequential decision problem, where states can be perceived exactly, and the current state and action selected determine a probability distribution on future states. Essentially, the outcome of applying an action to a state depends only on the current action and state (and not on preceding actions or states).
10.  **Dynamic programming (DP) —** is a class of solution methods for solving sequential decision problems with a compositional cost structure. Richard Bellman was one of the principal founders of this approach.
11.  **Monte Carlo methods** — A class of methods for learning of value functions, which estimates the value of a state by running many trials starting at that state, then averages the total rewards received on those trials.
12.  **Temporal Difference (TD) algorithms** — A class of learning methods, based on the idea of comparing temporally successive predictions. Possibly the single most fundamental idea in all of reinforcement learning.
13.  **Model** — The agent’s view of the environment, which maps state-action pairs to probability distributions over states. Note that not every reinforcement learning agent uses a model of its environment

## Agent
Contains ..
### Agent State
- Environment State
The history is everything the agent has observed

$$
H_{t}= O_{0},A_{0},R_{0}\dots
$$
The history $H_{t}$ is used to construct the agent state $S_{t}$ as there is no other data to consider
**Full Observability** the agent knows the Environment State
### Fully observable environments
[[Markovian Observavility]]

### Partially observable environments
The environment is not [[Markovian Observavility]] (fog of war for example)

Agent State exact def
$S_{t+1} = u(S_{t}, A_{t}, R_{t+1}, O_{t+1})$
u: is called the "state update function"
S should be a condenstation of all history 

## Policy

A **policy** is a mapping of states to actions 
Defines the agent's behaviour
#### Deterministic
$A=\pi(S)$
#### Stochastic
$\pi(A|S) = P(A|S)$

## Value Function

Discount factor $\gamma \in[0,1]$ helping to make it desirable to achieve a reward ASAP
$$
V_{\pi}=\mathbb{E}[G_{t}|S_{t},\pi]
$$
$G_{t} = R_{t+1}+\gamma G_{t+1}$
$v_{\pi}(S)=\mathbb{E}[R_{t+1}+\gamma v_{\pi}(S_{t+1})|S_{t}=s,A_{t}\approx\pi(s)]$
with $,A_{t}\approx\pi(s)]$ means that $A_{t}$ is chosen  with the policy $\pi$
This is a **Bellman Equation**
Also exists if we want to find the optimal
$v_{*}(S)= \underset{a}max{}\mathbb{E}[R_{t+1}+\gamma v_{\pi}(S_{t+1})|S_{t}=s,A_{t}=\pi(s)]$
**We will almost always approximate the value functions**

## Model
- A **model** predicts what the environment will do next
Can predict the next state and or next rewards
- $\mathcal{P}(s,a,s')\approx p(S_{t+1} = s' | S_{t}=s, A_{t}=a)$
- $\mathcal{R}\approx \mathbb{E}[R_{t+1}=r'|S_{t}=s,A_{t}=a]$

/Science/Sensory-Motor-Rythmes.content: The **sensorimotor rhythm** (**SMR**) is a [brain wave](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_oscillation "Neural oscillation"). It is an oscillatory idle rhythm of synchronized electric brain activity. It appears in spindles in recordings of [EEG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EEG "EEG"), [MEG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetoencephalography "Magnetoencephalography"), and [ECoG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECoG "ECoG") over the [sensorimotor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex "Motor cortex"). For most individuals, the frequency of the SMR is in the range of 13 to 15 Hz.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensorimotor_rhythm#cite_note-1)

/Science/Shattered.title: Shattered
/Science/Shattered.content: An arrangement of points can be shattered if **any subset** of this arrangement can be isolated and put into one class. Say, you want to test if a certain arrangement (not all possible arrangements but only one particular arrangement) of n points can be shattered by a certain type of classifiers. Then you first test if any single point can be isolated. Then, if any 2 points can be isolated, then if any 3 points, etc, till any n-1 points of that particular arrangement.

/Science/VC-dimensions.title: VC dimensions
/Science/VC-dimensions.content:
In Vapnik–Chervonenkis theory, the Vapnik–Chervonenkis (VC) dimension is **a measure of the capacity (complexity, expressive power, richness, or flexibility) of a set of functions that can be learned by a statistical binary classification algorithm**.


The definition of VC dimension is: if **there exists** a set of n points that can be [[Shattered]] by the classifier and **there is no** set of n+1 points that can be shattered by the classifier, then the VC dimension of the classifier is **n**.

The definition does not say: if **any set** of n points can be shattered by the classifier...

$$

$$
looking for the vector that after being transformed by $A$ lands on $\vec{v}$
- If $\det(a)\neq0$ then the space is not squished onto a single dimension, so their is only one vector that after the transformation $A$ lands on $\vec{v}$.
- If $\det(a)= 0$ then their is **one or less solutions !!!** Because the arrival space is $\vec{v}$ has to be on the arrival line when you squish the space, which is unlikely but possible.
- If $\vec{v}$ is on the [[Column Space]] of $A$ then $\vec{x}$ has solutions. Else it hasn't (I think)

- The [[Kernel]] can help us to understand how the set of all possible solutions can look like
### Computation

\vec{x} = A^{-1}\vec{v}
$$
Uses the properties of [[Inverse Matrix]]
